Notes for GCC 3.x
-----------------

 - installation:

   To be able to use GCC 2.x and GCC 3.x at the same time, its recommended
   to install the frontend programs in bin/ with an added "3" eg. as gcc3.
   Executing an older GCC version from the V3 frontend is possible with
   -V<version> if the frontend for <version> is installed as gcc-<version>.

   *Don't* extract or copy everything directly into GG:! Extract into a
   temp directory and remove unwanted stuff from there, eg.

     from bin: c++, cpp, gccbug, m68k-amigaos-#?
     from lib: libiberty.a

   Then add a suffix to the remaining programs in bin.
   Its also recommended to move

     <extract-dir>/lib/lib#?.a to lib/gcc/m68k-amigaos/<this version>

   to keep the old installation working.

 - Bugs:

   The AmigaOS/68k port of GCC3 has some known (and probably some unknown)
   bugs:

   There is a bug when using -fbaserel and -fstrength-reduce (which is
   automatcally enabled with -O2 and higher). As a workaround the AmigaOS/68k
   port currently disables strength-reduction if -fbaserel is used.

   Another bug exists with explicit register arguments and function pointers:

       void (*testfunc) (void (*)(int) __asm("a3"));

   The compiler says:

       error: parse error before ')' token

   However, if the above is rewritten like this:

       void (*testfunc) (void (*dummy)(int) __asm("a3"));

   then everything works.
   This bug was found by Fabio Alemagna in the GCC 3.3 port and is still
   present.

   GCC3 exposes a libnix shortcomming in its stdio implementation: generated
   code might reference unavailable functions: getc, getchar, putc, putchar.
   These functions might also be referenced by libstdc++.a. At the end of
   this document you can find usable versions of these functions.

 - OS inlines:

   To use GCC 3.x its necessary to install a new version of inline/macros.h
   if the used OS inline headers are based on LP macros. Previous versions
   of the file macros.h used the GCC extensions "extended asm" and "statement
   expression" incorrectly. GCC 3.x does detect and reject these broken
   constructs in the older macros.h versions. However, the corrected version
   still had problems and GCC3 could create broken code. Once again a new
   macros.h header file can be found in contrib/.
   Depending on the used inline type different actions have to be taken.
   Beware, fd2pragma upto 2.171 generates incorrect inlines for certain
   special types!
   Its _strongly_ recommended to read the extensions chapter of the GCC
   documentation.

 - inlining:

   Starting with GCC 3.1 "static inline" is handled _differently_ compared
   with previous GCC releases. Former GCC versions inlined functions marked
   with "static inline" unconditionally. GCC 3.1 and newer may choose to
   _ignore_ the inline hint! To get the previous behaviour an attribute must
   be added:

      __attribute__((always_inline))

   The attribute should only be added for 3.1 or newer. Older versions
   ignore the attribute but output a warning, so beware.

 - speed:

   GCC3 is significantly slower than previous versions and needs more
   memory, YMMV though.

 - building:

   By default, libgcc.a is built with debug information. To disable that
   remove -g from gcc/Makefile:LIBGCC2_DEBUG_CFLAGS _after_ configuration.

   By default, GCC uses -O2 when compiling. This can be overridden eg. at
   configure time like this (bourne shell style):

     CFLAGS= CXXFLAGS= <complete configure command line>

   At build time the flags can be set like this:

     gmake CFLAGS=-O CXXFLAGS=-O

   If possible -O2 should be used since GCC 3.3+ generates much better code
   with it.

   Using GNUmake is _highly_ recommended.

   The AmigaOS port has some hardcoded paths in xm-amigaos.h for the native
   installation which use /gg as prefix. As long as this matches --prefix=
   during configuration, everything is fine.


Thats all, good luck!

libnix additions:

-- getc.c --
#include <stdio.h>
int (getc)(FILE *stream)
{ return fgetc(stream); }
-- getchar.c --
#include <stdio.h>
int (getchar)(void)
{ return fgetc(stdin); }
-- putc.c --
#include <stdio.h>
int (putc)(int c,FILE *stream)
{ return fputc(c,stream); }
-- putchar.c --
#include <stdio.h>
int (putchar)(int c)
{ return fputc(c,stdout); }
